snippet.textDisplay: TBH being vegan is not "very restrictive", there are plant-based versions of nearly every non-vegan food that you enjoy (plant-based sausages, burgers, orange chicken, etc.).  You're changing your habit of eating animal products which has been engrained in most of us for so many years so a big change like that always seems difficult at first. However, when you realize the positive impact that you're having on so many animals, your health, and the environment you definitely need to stay motivated and committed to being vegan✊. I'll admite it can be less convenient at times though

snippet.textDisplay: Vegan for 30 days hey. Wow. So tough. Been vegan for years, haven't eaten disgusting meat for over 15 years now, and doh - still alive! Fitter than many of my contemporaries, many are on drugs because of their meat/dairy/egg diets, and sadly some have passed - heart attacks mainly, some cancer. Why do so many people find it extreme to go vegan when it is our natural diet? Vegan eating is so much more healthier. Eating animals kills and brings disease. So obvious, but people just don't want to know. They ignore facts due to their lifestyles, cultures, false beliefs, etc. But encouragingly the world is changing. More and more are seeing the light. Vegan = better health, better planet health, better for animals, better for all. Any arguments against don't stack up under scrutiny :0)

snippet.textDisplay: I really don’t like the diabetes guy’s opinion on fat. Pleeeaase include enough fat sources into your plantbased diet. Otherwise you will feel sluggish and tired. Fat is important and a little bit of oil won’t kill you, especially when you’re trying to gain. Diabetes is mainly caused by having consumed too much cholesterol  rich food (meat & dairy) so having a mainly whole food plantbased diet you will not have to worry so much about diabetes in the first place. Include nuts and seeds like walnuts, hemp seeds etc. which are very high in omega 3 & 6 and loads and loads of nut & seed butters if you’re trying to maintain a healthy plantbased diet. Nice Video! :)
